<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1972,2033]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="122" pageId="19" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,324,1972,1997]" pageId="19" pageNumber="120">Redescription.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[422,506,1973,1997]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="19" pageNumber="120" unit="mm" value="31.0">31 mm</quantity>
. The species has an elongate, oval body that is wider at the dorsal extreme; dark chestnut-brown in color. The pronotum is wider than it is long (
<figureCitation box="[862,944,2008,2033]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 69" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[346,1317,257,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[252,1336,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 69. Phyllophaga gigantea adult female. Pronotum, dorsal view (63), right antenna (64), right protarsal claw (65), right metatibia (66), abdomen apex appearance, lateral view (67), frontal view (68), ventral view (69). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219012/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="120">
Fig. 
<number box="[915,944,2008,2033]" pageId="19" pageNumber="120" value="63.0">63</number>
</figureCitation>
) with surface densely covered in setae and finely crenulate lateral margins. The clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[666,748,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 69" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[346,1317,257,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[252,1336,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 69. Phyllophaga gigantea adult female. Pronotum, dorsal view (63), right antenna (64), right protarsal claw (65), right metatibia (66), abdomen apex appearance, lateral view (67), frontal view (68), ventral view (69). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219012/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="122">
Fig. 
<number box="[719,748,151,176]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="63.0">63</number>
</figureCitation>
) is wide, slightly sinuous, concave with raised margins and a densely punctate surface; vertex is profusely covered with small setae. Antennae (
<figureCitation box="[1084,1166,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 69" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[346,1317,257,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[252,1336,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 69. Phyllophaga gigantea adult female. Pronotum, dorsal view (63), right antenna (64), right protarsal claw (65), right metatibia (66), abdomen apex appearance, lateral view (67), frontal view (68), ventral view (69). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219012/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="122">
Fig. 
<number box="[1137,1166,188,213]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="64.0">64</number>
</figureCitation>
) have 
<number box="[1244,1272,188,212]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="10.0">10</number>
antennomeres with long and compact antennal clubs. Tarsal claws (Fig, 
<number box="[806,835,223,248]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="65.0">65</number>
) are cleft, with a sharp ventral tooth, longer than the average length of the others, and located in a central position. Metatibiae (
<figureCitation box="[994,1076,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 69" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[346,1317,257,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[252,1336,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 69. Phyllophaga gigantea adult female. Pronotum, dorsal view (63), right antenna (64), right protarsal claw (65), right metatibia (66), abdomen apex appearance, lateral view (67), frontal view (68), ventral view (69). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219012/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="122">
Fig. 
<number box="[1047,1076,260,285]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="66.0">66</number>
</figureCitation>
) are flat, long, cylindrical, with three teeth; the second tooth pronounced and the third tooth smaller, with two sharp spurs, the inner spur being shorter than the outer spur; two transversal carinae are present in the dorsolateral region, one at a mid-position and the other at a basal position. Pygidial plate (
<figureCitation box="[658,787,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 63 – 69" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[346,1317,257,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[252,1336,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 63 – 69. Phyllophaga gigantea adult female. Pronotum, dorsal view (63), right antenna (64), right protarsal claw (65), right metatibia (66), abdomen apex appearance, lateral view (67), frontal view (68), ventral view (69). Scale: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219012/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="122">
Figs 
<number box="[716,787,367,392]" pageId="21" pageNumber="122" value="68.0" valueMax="69.0" valueMin="67.0">67–69</number>
</figureCitation>
) is convex with abundant erect, short and medium-sized setae on the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
